               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18700711-name-327" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18700711-name-327" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18700711-name-327" type="surname" value="LLOYD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18700711-name-327" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>WILLIAM HENRY LLOYD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a carpenter, of Lamb's Passage, Chis<lb></lb>well Street—about 1 o'clock, on the morning of 30th June, I was in Charterhouse Street—there was a crowd there, and I and two others went over—as soon as we got on the footpath the prisoner came alongside of me and made a snatch at my watch—I snatched at his hand, but caught the chain instead—he ran away—I went after him and called "Stop thief!"—a policeman stopped him on the steps of the Holborn Viaduct—this watch (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) is mine—it was found close to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18700711-name-328" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18700711-name-328" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18700711-name-328" type="surname" value="MARJORAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18700711-name-328" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE MARJORAM</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 9, Adelaide Place, Lower Victoria Street—I was with Lloyd—I saw the prisoner's hand go away from his pocket—he ran away, and we after him—I never lost sight of him—he was on the steps of the Viaduct—the watch fell at my feet, and was picked up by a stranger—I heard the sound of broken glass.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
